  "enhanced_information": "For a 50-year-old man diagnosed with coronary artery disease and an LDL cholesterol level of 150-165 mg/dl, the most appropriate initial therapy is statins. Statins are highly effective in reducing LDL cholesterol, which is crucial for managing coronary artery disease. They not only lower LDL levels but also significantly improve cardiovascular outcomes, making them the preferred choice in such clinical scenarios. Other options like Gemfibrozil, Nicotinic acid, and Bile acid binding resins, while having roles in lipid management, are either less effective in specifically targeting LDL cholesterol or have less favorable side effect profiles compared to statins. The evidence path confirming the role of statins (Hydroxymethylglutaryl-CoA Reductase Inhibitors) in treating coronary arteriosclerosis supports their use as the primary treatment in this case."
